M. From his elevation to his death , Justinian governed the Roman empire thirty eight years , seven months , and thirteen days . 
According to the vicissitudes of courage or servitude , of favor or disgrace , Procopius successively composed the history , the panegyric , and the satire of his own times . 
The conscious dignity of independence was subdued by the hopes and fears of a slave and the secretary of Belisarius labored for pardon and reward in the six books of the Imperial edifices . 
From these various materials , I shall now proceed to describe the reign of Justinian , which will deserve and occupy an ample space . 
The present chapter will explain the elevation and character of Theodora , the factions of the circus , and the peaceful administration of the sovereign of the East . 
