The fortifications of Europe and Asia were multiplied by Justinian but the repetition of those timid and fruitless precautions exposes , to a philosophic eye , the debility of the empire . 
Yet these military works , which exhausted the public treasure , could not remove the just apprehensions of Justinian and his European subjects . 
The Straits of Thermopylae , which seemed to protect , but which had so often betrayed , the safety of Greece , were diligently strengthened by the labors of Justinian . 
The long wall , as it was emphatically styled , was a work as disgraceful in the object , as it was respectable in the execution . 
