The character of Theophilus is a rare example in which religious zeal has allowed , and perhaps magnified , the virtues of a heretic and a persecutor . 
Nor was Theophilus content with this extravagant satisfaction his zeal converted a civil trespass into a criminal act and the unfortunate patrician was stripped and scourged in the public place of Constantinople . 
Yet in the crime , or the suspicion , of treason , that judge is of all others the most credulous and partial . 
