This affectation of unseasonable wit displeased the Imperial lover he turned aside in disgust Icasia concealed her mortification in a convent and the modest silence of Theodora was rewarded with the golden apple . 
She deserved the love , but did not escape the severity , of her lord . 
Yet his last choice intrusted her with the guardianship of the empire and her son Michael , who was left an orphan in the fifth year of his age . 
After thirteen years of a prudent and frugal administration , she perceived the decline of her influence but the second Irene imitated only the virtues of her predecessor . 
Whatever might have been the maternal care of Theodora in the education of Michael the Third , her unfortunate son was a king before he was a man . 
At the age of eighteen , he rejected her authority , without feeling his own incapacity to govern the empire and himself . 
Like Nero , he delighted in the amusements of the theatre , and sighed to be surpassed in the accomplishments in which he should have blushed to excel . 
The unnatural lusts which had degraded even the manhood of Nero , were banished from the world yet the strength of Michael was consumed by the indulgence of love and intemperance . 
But the most extraordinary feature in the character of Michael , is the profane mockery of the religion of his country . 
Nor were these impious spectacles concealed from the eyes of the city . 
In a campaign against the Saracens , he betrayed both imbecility and cowardice . 
exhibits a genuine picture of the revolution of the most illustrious families . 
